Image shows 'ribbons' of sand and patterned stripes known as linear dunes in the Erg Chech, a desolate sand sea in southwestern Algeria . 
  Linear dunes are straight ridges of sand that have been known to measure as long as 99 miles (160km) But the exact cause of these longitudinal structures is not known . 
  Nasa captured the image using its Landsat 7 satellite . 
  The colours were caused as rays of sunlight hit the sand . 
 